<p><b>Citrine</b> is a general purpose <a href="/wiki/Programming_language" title="Programming language">programming language</a> for <a href="/wiki/Unix-like" title="Unix-like">Unix-like</a> operating systems. It focuses on readability and maintainability. Readability is achieved by syntactic and conceptual minimalism. The language is heavily inspired by <a href="/wiki/Smalltalk" title="Smalltalk">Smalltalk</a> and <a href="/wiki/Self_(programming_language)" title="Self (programming language)">Self</a> but has some very distinctive features. Like Smalltalk, Citrine treats everything as an object and focuses on sending messages to these objects. However unlike Smalltalk, Citrine lacks the concept of a class. In this regard, Citrine is more like Self and <a href="/wiki/JavaScript" title="JavaScript">JavaScript</a> because it uses <a href="/wiki/Prototype-based_programming" title="Prototype-based programming">prototypes</a>. The combination of Smalltalk like messages and prototypes is what makes Citrine unique.</p>
<p></p>
<div id="toc" class="toc">
<div id="toctitle">
